{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/speech-analysis-of-vowels-for-japanese-language-fdee6ec1a4ba", "time": 1683002471.9096582, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/speech-analysis-of-vowels-for-japanese-language-fdee6ec1a4ba/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Acoustic & Articulatory Analysis on Japanese Vowels | by Pei Seng Tan | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Acoustic & Articulatory Analysis on Japanese Vowels", "description": "In order to build a speech recognizer or speech to text converter for English or Japanese, typically you need three components, which are an acoustic model, a lexicon model and a language model to\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "http://www.fon.hum.uva.nl/praat/download_win.html", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 7}], "all_paragraphs": ["In order to build a speech recognizer or speech to text converter for English or Japanese, typically you need three components, which are an acoustic model, a lexicon model and a language model to strike a success.", "Most of the researchers will normally collect the speech signals from the native speakers in order to maintain the quality of an acoustic model.", "What if you really want to collect your own voice signals as the dataset for acoustic modelling? Or you wish to know how much does your pronunciation as a non-native speaker deviate from the native speakers?", "In the following parts, I am going to show you how to perform acoustic and articulatory analysis on Japanese vowels by using your own recorded voice as inputs.", "Firstly, you need to prepare the dataset by pronouncing some of the words using your own voice and recording them using your headset. Make sure that the surrounding environment is highly silent to maintain the quality of the voice recordings.", "Each voice recording should contain only one word. For each vowel, find five words with the particular vowel and record with your own voice.", "The words that are chosen for the demonstration are shown in the table below. The underlined characters are the vowels that are going to be further analyzed.", "After all the voice recordings are ready, the next procedure will be annotating the voice with phonemes. The tool that I would like to introduce is Praat, which is a free computer software package for speech analytics in phonetics. You can download it here.", "The steps that you need to perform for voice annotation include:", "Human speech production consists of two stages, which are source and filter.", "The source, which is the vocal folds, will vibrate to generate a complex periodic voice signal. The frequency of the complex periodic voice signal is known as the fundamental frequency.", "On the other hand, the filter, which is the vocal tract, will change its shape with the aid of articulation to modify the harmonics of the complex periodic voice signal. The frequency of the voice signal after modification is known as formant.", "The average of the first and second formants can be easily figured out by going to the menu bar, clicking Formant and choosing First Formant or Second Formant according to your necessity. Then, the average first and second formant for each vowel is obtained and the result is recorded as shown in the table below.", "After the average readings of the first and second formants for each vowel are collected, the graph of the values of the first formant versus the second formant is plotted. The former shows the result derived from my voice recordings whereas the latter shows the result derived from the voice recordings provided by the Japanese native speakers.", "By comparing two charts drawn above:", "As a non-native speaker of Japanese, I figured out that my pronunciation for vowel \u201c\u3046/\u30a6(u)\u201d is slightly different compared to a Japanese native speaker. My pronunciation for other vowels looks good and are similar to Japanese native speakers. Instead of using the voice recording from Japanese native speakers for building the acoustic model, I can build my own acoustic model with self voice recordings.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Ffdee6ec1a4ba&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fspeech-analysis-of-vowels-for-japanese-language-fdee6ec1a4ba&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fspeech-analysis-of-vowels-for-japanese-language-fdee6ec1a4ba&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fspeech-analysis-of-vowels-for-japanese-language-fdee6ec1a4ba&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fspeech-analysis-of-vowels-for-japanese-language-fdee6ec1a4ba&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": 